liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: James Cameron, director of the Oscar-winning film Titanic, told ABC News Americahe finds the tragedy "astonishing and surreal." "I'm struck by the similarity of the Titanic disaster itself where the captain was repeatedly warned about ice ahead of his ship and yet he steamed into an ice field on a moonless night – and many people died as a result," he said. "It's a very similar tragedy where warnings went unheeded. "To take place at the same exact site with all the diving that's going on all around the world… I think it's just astonishing and surreal. He says the diving community is small and that he had known French diver Paul-Henri Nargeolet for 25 years. "For him to die tragically in this way is almost impossible for me to process." Cameron has completed 33 deep sea dives to the historic wreck, saying he's "spent more time on the ship than the captain did." "I also designed and built a sub to go to the deepest place in the ocean, three times deeper than the Titanic, so I understand the engineering and safety problems associated with building this type of vehicle," he adds.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Director James Cameron 'struck by the similarity' of the two Titanic disasters

children.content: James Cameron spoke to ABC America.
(ABC News America)
James Cameron
, director of the Oscar-winning film Titanic, told ABC News Americahe finds the tragedy "astonishing and surreal."

"I'm struck by the similarity of the Titanic disaster itself where the captain was repeatedly warned about ice ahead of his ship and yet he steamed into an ice field on a moonless night – and many people died as a result," he said.
"It's a very similar tragedy where warnings went unheeded.
"To take place at the same exact site with all the diving that's going on all around the world… I think it's just astonishing and surreal.
He says the diving community is small and that he had known French diver
Paul-Henri Nargeolet
for 25 years.
"For him to die tragically in this way is almost impossible for me to process."
Cameron has completed 33 deep sea dives to the historic wreck, saying he's "spent more time on the ship than the captain did."

"I also designed and built a sub to go to the deepest place in the ocean, three times deeper than the Titanic, so I understand the engineering and safety problems associated with building this type of vehicle," he adds.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Mauger says it's unclear when the submersible imploded, but it's unlikely it was in the past three days. "We know that as we've been prosecuting this search over the course of the last 72 hours, we've had sonar buoys ... and have not detected any catastrophic events," he says.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Timing of implosion unclear

children.content: Mauger says it's unclear when the submersible imploded, but it's unlikely it was in the past three days.
"We know that as we've been prosecuting this search over the course of the last 72 hours, we've had sonar buoys ... and have not detected any catastrophic events," he says.
